      Trump SPAC PIPE
   =20
 =20
In September, a company called Digital World Acquisition Corp. went public,=
 raising $287.5 million by selling stock to investors at $10 per share. DWA=
C=C2=A0is a special purpose acquisition company, or SPAC, a=C2=A0blind pool=
 to find another company to take public. The idea is that the SPAC puts the=
 money it raises into a bank account, finds a private company that wants to=
 go public, and merges with that target company. The target company gets th=
e money in the SPAC=E2=80=99s bank account=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0$287.5 milli=
on or so, in DWAC=E2=80=99s case =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the public shareholders=
 of the SPAC get back shares in the target company, which becomes a public =
company by merging with the SPAC. If the SPAC doesn=E2=80=99t find a deal w=
ithin two years, or if the shareholders don't like the deal it finds, they =
get their $10 back.[1]In October, DWAC announced its merger, and=C2=A0it wa=
s a doozy. The private company that DWAC will take public is Trump Media & =
Technology Group, which is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0a =E2=80=A6=C2=A0media =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0and =E2=80=A6=C2=A0technology =E2=80=A6=C2=A0group? =E2=80=A6=C2=A0af=
filiated with Donald Trump. Nobody had heard of TMTG before it announced it=
s SPAC merger, and nobody has heard all that much about it since. =E2=80=9C=
Trump Media & Technology Group (=E2=80=98TMTG=E2=80=99) will soon be launch=
ing a social network, named =E2=80=98TRUTH Social,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D said t=
he merger announcement, promising a beta launch in November. It=C2=A0missed=
 that deadline. A test version of the site seemed to be just a clone of ope=
n-source social network Mastodon. TMTG=E2=80=99s website has a =E2=80=9Ccom=
pany overview=E2=80=9D slide deck=C2=A0that contains no business informatio=
n=C2=A0and does not mention anyone involved in building its supposed techno=
logy.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThis appears to be a shell company buying a shell compa=
ny,=E2=80=9D wrote Dan Primack.I  wrote at the time:If Donald Trump announc=
ed =E2=80=9Chey I=E2=80=99m gonna do a social media company, buy some stock=
,=E2=80=9D people would buy some stock. And then he=E2=80=99d get a lot of =
money. And then if the social media platform did not end up being profitabl=
e =E2=80=94 as I cannot imagine it would be! =E2=80=94 then he would, uh, s=
till have that money? And if the social media platform did not end up being=
 launched =E2=80=94 if Trump and his crack team of technologists just could=
n=E2=80=99t actually build a well-functioning online social network =E2=80=
=94 then he would, uh, still have that money? And if there was no crack tea=
m of technologists at all, if nobody even tried to build the social media p=
latform =E2=80=94 then you see where I am going with this right?Anyway. The=
 deal is that DWAC will put in the money in its bank account =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0about $293 million =E2=80=94=C2=A0and get about 37 million shares of TMT=
G[2]; the current owners of TMTG =E2=80=94=C2=A0presumably Donald Trump and=
 =E2=80=A6=C2=A0some =E2=80=A6=C2=A0other people? =E2=80=94=C2=A0will get a=
 variable number of shares that I am just going to call 125.8 million.[3] S=
o roughly speaking Trump is selling about=C2=A023% of his company for $293 =
million.Before the merger was announced, DWAC=E2=80=99s stock traded public=
ly between call it $9.92 and $9.97 per share. This is=C2=A0normal for a SPA=
C in late 2021: SPACs were hot in early 2021 but the trend faded, and these=
 days a SPAC share=C2=A0pretty much represents the right to get back $10 at=
 some indefinite point in the next two years. The day after the merger was =
announced, DWAC closed at $45.50. The next day, it closed at $94.20. It has=
 not closed below $40 since. On Friday it closed at $44.97.=C2=A0This sound=
s good, but it is actually somewhat awkward for Trump and TMTG. The price i=
s too high. Trump is selling about 23% of his company for $293 million, but=
 the public market says that that stake is worth about $1.7 billion.[4]The =
public market, I should emphasize, is saying that based on=C2=A0nothing. As=
 of last Friday, there was=C2=A0absolutely no financial or technical or bus=
iness information about TMTG available to the public; so far there is almos=
t no sign that TMTG is actually building a social network or a streaming pl=
atform or anything else.[5]But the market says that TMTG is worth $44.97 pe=
r share. And TMTG is selling stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0to DWAC =E2=80=94=C2=A0at=
 $10 per share.[6] Seems like sort of a bad deal.The obvious trade here for=
 TMTG =E2=80=94=C2=A0essentially a meme stock riding high on retail enthusi=
asm =E2=80=94=C2=A0is to go sell more stock. Peel off a billion-dollar offe=
ring at $40 per share: That=E2=80=99s 25 million shares, less than it is is=
suing to DWAC, but for more than three times as much money. Great. I  say t=
his all the time: If you=E2=80=99re a meme company and everyone is buying y=
our stock, the move is to sell your stock.But TMTG=C2=A0can=E2=80=99t do th=
at. TMTG is not a public company yet; it can=E2=80=99t sell stock to retail=
 investors. DWAC=C2=A0is=C2=A0a public company, but SPACs can=E2=80=99t jus=
t go sell stock at market prices; SPACs are strange blind-pool money-in-tru=
st creatures that come with investor protections, and selling a claim on $1=
0 in cash for $40 seems like a no-no.[7]=C2=A0Still this is the right line =
of thinking=C2=A0if you=E2=80=99re Trump, or TMTG, or their advisers. Find =
someone to buy $1 billion of stock at a lot more than $10 per share, since =
the stock is trading at a lot more than $10 per share.Well. Most SPACs, whe=
n they announce a merger, also announce a PIPE. A PIPE is a private investm=
ent in public equity: Some big institutional investors agree to invest in t=
he combined public company alongside the SPAC. The PIPE is useful for two r=
easons. One, it guarantees the company some money: SPAC investors are allow=
ed to take their $10 back, but PIPE investors normally make firm commitment=
s to invest. So if you do a SPAC-plus-PIPE deal, you=E2=80=99re definitely =
raising some money. Second, it validates the SPAC price: The public investo=
rs in the SPAC, who have perhaps never heard of the company they are about =
to buy, can be more confident because some big sophisticated investors have=
 negotiated to invest in the company, often =E2=80=94=C2=A0though not alway=
s =E2=80=94=C2=A0on the same trems as the SPAC investors.When TMTG and DWAC=
 announced their merger, they did not announce a PIPE. This was not surpris=
ing! The whole subtext here was that=C2=A0TMTG was not a real company; it h=
as never disclosed any financial statements or business plans or operating =
executives or anything. No big institutional investors wanted to commit a l=
ot of money to buy stock in a phantom company.But since the stock traded up=
, things are different, and TMTG and DWAC have  talked a  lot about raising=
