0, and it does not yet seem to be effective. This seems like the typical ti=
me frame.[11] I=E2=80=99m just averaging the $30 and $25 assumed closing pr=
ices. Actually the formula would volume-weight them, which would probably g=
ive more weight to the first day but who knows.[12] By the way that slide a=
lso has a =E2=80=9CPro Forma Ownership=E2=80=9D table that is ... wrong? It=
 lists pro forma ownership at an assumed stock price of about $72.76 per sh=
are, and shows the PIPE investors getting 13.7 million shares in that scena=
rio. But that=E2=80=99s not how the deal documents work: The PIPE investors=
 have a valuation *cap* of $33.60; they can never get fewer than 29.8 milli=
on shares. Presumably this table was shown to potential PIPE investors befo=
re the deal was finalized, and has not been updated. (Another smaller error=
 is that it shows TMTG shareholders getting 87.5 million shares of the comb=
ined company, or 127.5 million with the full earnout, which is based on $10=
 per share in DWAC=E2=80=99s trust; in fact there is about $10.20 per share=
 in the trust=C2=A0and the real numbers seem to be 85.8 million and 125.8 m=
illion, see footnote 3.)[13] The all-time=C2=A0champion of this is Frank Pe=
rkins Hixon Jr., who tipped his girlfriend and his father, Frank Perkins Hi=
xon, about some inside information that the girlfriend and Frank Sr. then t=
raded on. Confronted with a list of names, including both the girlfriend an=
d Frank Sr., Frank Perkins Hixon Jr. said =E2=80=9Cnope, don=E2=80=99t reco=
gnize any of them.=E2=80=9D This did not go well.
